# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aberdeen-student-show
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] After being appointed managing director of the BBC in 1922, John Reith instigated a programme of expansion of the radio network in the United Kingdom, increasing the number of local stations from three to twenty in a relatively short period of time.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] Aberdeen was one of the first new stations to be put on air.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] The opening ceremony for the station was conducted by the Marquis of Aberdeen at 9pm on 10 October 1923, followed by a performance from the Band of the 2nd Gordon Highlanders.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] Those attending the launch included the Lord Provost of Aberdeen, BBC MD John Reith, station director R.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] Jeffery, and chief engineer Peter Eckersley.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] Inside the studio, broadcasters used a single microphone on a wheeled base, which severely restricted the number of users at any one time.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] Being transmitted from the Aberdeen Steam Laundry Company building, the signal then travelled to an aerial slung between two Marconi radio masts sited beside some nearby electrical generators (which frequently interfered with broadcasts).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] Although the transmitter was of low power, it was reported that the first programmes were heard in Norway and, similarly, subsequent broadcasts more than a year later could be heard in the United States during "International Radio Week".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] During a live six-hour transmission day, the station supplied a mix of light music, comedy, news, and sports reporting.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] A former Scottish football referee, Peter Craigmyle, broadcast a 15-minute programme once a week devoted to previewing sports events.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] The station had its own "2BD Repertory Company" with members including William Mair, Daisy Moncur, Grace Wilson and George Dewar.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] It had its own 12-piece orchestra, supplemented by harmonica player Donald Davidson, although they were reduced to eight members in 1926, and disbanded after the demise of the station.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] Comedy was supplied by entertainers such as Jessie R.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] Allan, and many other artistes appeared before the microphone, including local boy Harry Gordon and character actress Mabel Constanduris.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] In May 1925, 2BD's premises were extended to take in number 15 Belmont Street; however, in 1926 the "Geneva Frequency Plan" cut the number of available wavelengths by 50%.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] 2BD's frequency was changed to 610 kHz (491.8 m) with effect from 14 November 1926 and then a month later – because of the interference caused by 2BD having to share a frequency with the BBC's Birmingham station, 5IT – to 600 kHz (500 m).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/2bd] The BBC broadcasting centre subsequently moved to larger premises in Beechgrove Terrace, which were demolished and replaced by a new building on the same site in the year 2000.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Set on the bare stage of a Broadway theater, the musical is centered on seventeen Broadway dancers auditioning for spots on a chorus line.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] *A Chorus Line* provides a glimpse into the personalities of the performers and the choreographer, as they describe the events that have shaped their lives and their decisions to become dancers.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Following several workshops and an Off-Broadway production, *A Chorus Line* opened at the Shubert Theatre on Broadway July 25, 1975, directed by Michael Bennett and co-choreographed by Bennett and Bob Avian.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] An unprecedented box office and critical hit, the musical received twelve Tony Award nominations and won nine, in addition to the 1976 Pulitzer Prize for Drama.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The original Broadway production ran for 6,137 performances, becoming the longest-running production in Broadway history until surpassed by *Cats* in 1997, and the longest-running Broadway musical originally produced in the US, until surpassed in 2011 by the revival of *Chicago*.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] It remains the seventh longest-running Broadway show ever.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] *A Chorus Line*'s success has spawned many successful productions worldwide.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] It began a lengthy run in the West End in 1976 winning the Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Musical and was revived on Broadway in 2006, and in the West End in 2013.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The show opens during an audition for an upcoming Broadway production.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The formidable director Zach and his assistant choreographer Larry put the 24 dancers through their paces.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Every dancer is desperate for work ("I Hope I Get It").
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] After a round of cuts, 17 dancers remain.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Zach tells them he is looking for a strong eight-member dancing chorus of four boys and four girls.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Wanting to learn more about them, he asks the dancers to introduce themselves.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Reluctantly, the dancers reveal their pasts.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The stories generally progress chronologically from early life experiences through adulthood to their chosen career.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The first candidate, Mike Costa, explains that he is the youngest of 12 children.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] He recalls his first experience with dance, watching his sister Rosalie's dance class when he was a preschooler ("I Can Do That").
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Mike replaced her one day when she refused to go to class—and he stayed.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] As Bobby Mills tries to hide his unhappy childhood by making jokes, the other dancers distrust this strange audition process and debate what they should reveal to Zach ("And..."), but since they all need the job, the session continues.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Zach is angered that the streetwise Sheila Bryant is seemingly not taking the audition seriously.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Opening up, she reveals that her mother married at a young age and her father neither cared about nor loved them.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] At age six she realized, as had fellow auditionees Bebe Benzenheimer and Maggie Winslow, that ballet helped her escape her unhappy family life ("At the Ballet").
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Scatterbrained and tone-deaf Kristine Urich-DeLuca laments being unable to sing, while her husband Al finishes her phrases in tune ("Sing!").
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Diana Morales describes her horrible high school acting class ("Nothing"), Don Kerr remembers his first job at a nightclub and Judy Turner reflects on her problematic childhood while others talk about their parents' opinions ("Mother").
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Greg Gardner discusses discovering his homosexuality and Richie Walters recounts nearly becoming a kindergarten teacher ("Gimme the Ball").
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Finally, the newly-buxom Val Clark explains that talent alone isn't everything without good looks, and plastic surgery can really help improve one's image and career prospects ("Dance: Ten, Looks: Three").
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The dancers go downstairs to learn a song for the audition's next section, but experienced dancer Cassie Ferguson, who has had notable successes as a soloist, stays onstage to talk to Zach.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] They have a history together: Zach had previously cast her in featured parts, and they had lived together for several years.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Zach tells Cassie that she is too good for the chorus and shouldn't be at this audition.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] However, she explains her current inability to find solo work and is willing to "come home" to the chorus where she can at least express her passion for dance ("The Music and the Mirror").
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Zach relents and sends her downstairs to learn the dance combination.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Cassie and Zach's complex relationship resurfaces during a run-through of the number created to showcase an unnamed star ("One").
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Zach confronts Cassie, feeling that she is "dancing down," and they rehash the issues in their relationship and her career.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Zach points to the machine-like movement of the other dancers, who have all blended together and will probably never be recognized individually, and mockingly asks if she wants this.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Cassie defiantly defends the dancers: "I'd be proud to be one of them.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] They're wonderful....They're all special.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] I'd be happy to be dancing in that line.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] During a tap sequence, Paul falls and injures his knee that recently underwent surgery.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] After Paul is carried off to the hospital, all at the audition stand in disbelief, realizing that their careers can also end in an instant.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Zach asks the remaining dancers what they will do when they can no longer dance.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Led by Diana, they assert that whatever happens next in their lives and/or careers, they will be free of regret for pursuing their dreams ("What I Did for Love").
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The final eight dancers are selected: Mike, Cassie, Bobby, Judy, Richie, Val, Mark, and Diana.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] "One" (Reprise/Finale) begins with an individual bow for each of the 19 characters, their hodgepodge rehearsal clothes replaced by identical spangled gold costumes.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] As each dancer joins the group, it is suddenly difficult to distinguish one from the other: ironically, each character who was an individual to the audience seems now to be an anonymous member of a never-ending ensemble.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The original cast album was Issued by Columbia Records (PS33581).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The musical was formed from several taped workshop sessions with Broadway dancers, known as "gypsies," including eight who eventually appeared in the original cast.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The sessions were originally hosted by dancers Michon Peacock and Tony Stevens.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The first taped session occurred at the Nickolaus Exercise Center on January 26, 1974.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] They hoped that they would form a professional dance company to make workshops for Broadway dancers.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Michael Bennett was invited to join the group primarily as an observer, but quickly took control of the proceedings.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Although Bennett's involvement has been challenged, there has been no question about Kirkwood and Dante's authorship.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] In later years, Bennett's claim that *A Chorus Line* had been his brainchild resulted not only in hard feelings but a number of lawsuits as well.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] During the workshop sessions, random characters would be chosen at the end for the chorus jobs based on their performance quality, resulting in a different "cast" being selected every run-through.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] However, several of the costumers objected to this ending, citing the stress of having to change random actors in time for the finale.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] This resulted in the ending being cut in exchange for the same set of characters being "cast." Marvin Hamlisch, who wrote *A Chorus Line*'s score, recalled how, during the first previews, audiences seemed put off by something in the story.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] This problem was solved when actress Marsha Mason told Bennett that Cassie (Donna McKechnie in the original production) should win the part in the end because she did everything right.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Bennett changed it so that Cassie would always win the part.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Additional Opening Night cast members Carole Schweid and John Mineo were understudies named "Barbara" and "Jarad", although they only went on covering other roles.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The production was nominated for 12 Tony Awards, winning nine: Best Musical, Best Musical Book, Best Score (Hamlisch and Kleban), Best Director, and Best Choreography, Best Actress (McKechnie), Best Featured Actor (Sammy Williams), Best Featured Actress (Bishop), and Best Lighting Design.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The show won the 1976 Pulitzer Prize for Drama, one of the few musicals ever to receive this honor, swept nearly all the main categories at the 1976 Drama Desk Awards, and the New York Drama Critics' Circle Award for Best Play of the season.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] In 1976, many of the original cast went on to perform in San Francisco.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Open roles were recast, and the play was again reviewed as the *"New" New York Company* which included Ann Reinking, Sandahl Bergman, Christopher Chadman, Justin Ross (who would go on to appear in the film), and Barbara Luna.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] When it closed, *A Chorus Line* was the longest running show in Broadway history until its record was surpassed by *Cats* in 1997.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] On September 29, 1983, Bennett and 332 *A Chorus Line* veterans gathered to celebrate the musical becoming the longest-running show in Broadway history.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Up to February 19, 1990, *A Chorus Line* had generated $146 million from its Broadway gross and $277 million in total U.S. grosses and had 6.5 million Broadway attendees.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] At the time, it was the second most profitable show in Broadway history after *Cats* with profits of $50 million (including ancillary income).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] 75% of the profits went to Papp's New York Shakespeare Festival and 25% to Bennett's Plum Productions.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Since its inception, the show's many worldwide productions, both professional and amateur, have been a major source of income for The Public Theater that Papp had founded.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] U.S. and international tours were mounted in 1976, including a sit-down engagement in Los Angeles at the Shubert Theatre.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] A London production opened in the West End at the Theatre Royal Drury Lane in 1976, initially with the International Cast from the US, including Jane Summerhays as Sheila.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The production ran for three years and won the Laurence Olivier Award as Best Musical of the Year in 1976, the first year the awards were presented.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The original British cast took over in 1977.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] It included Jean-Pierre Cassel as Zach, Diane Langton as Diana Morales, Jeff Shankley as Al, Michael Staniforth as Paul, Stephen Tate as Greg (later replacing Cassel as Zach) and Geraldine Gardner (aka Trudi van Doorn of *The Benny Hill Show*) as Sheila.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Elizabeth Seal was cast as Cassie but was replaced at the eleventh hour by her understudy Petra Siniawski who played the role for the entire British cast run.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The original Australian production opened in Sydney at Her Majesty's Theatre in May 1977 and moved to Melbourne's Her Majesty's Theatre in January 1978.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The cast featured Peta Toppano as Diana, David Atkins as Mike, and Ross Coleman as Paul.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] In 1980, under the direction of Roy Smith, the Teatro El Nacional of Buenos Aires produced a Spanish version of *A Chorus Line* lasting 10 months (and then only to make way for an already scheduled subsequent production).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] In Spain, the show opened in December 1984 at Teatre Tívoli in Barcelona, directed by Roy Smith and translated into Spanish by Nacho Artime and Jaime Azpilicueta, before transferring to Teatro Monumental in Madrid.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] In July 1986, *A Chorus Line* was produced in Italy for the first time.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] It premiered at the Nervi Festival of Dance in Genoa, followed by a five-week Italian tour.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The choreography was adapted for the festival's performing space by Baayork Lee who had played Connie in the original production and subsequently became a close collaborator of Michael Bennett, the original choreographer.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The German-language version was again directed by Lee and first opened in 1987 in Vienna, Austria, where it ran for one season followed by the German-language CD release produced by Jimmy Bowien in 1988.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The first—and as of 2016 only—professional Hungarian production of the musical opened its limited run on March 25, 1988, under the title **Michael Bennett emlékére** (*In Memory of Michael Bennett*).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] It was performed by Ódry Színpad (the company of the Academy of Drama and Film in Budapest) translated into Hungarian by György Gebora, and directed by Imre Kerényi.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The character Zach was renamed Michael and played by Kerényi.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The 2006 Broadway revival opened at the Gerald Schoenfeld Theater on October 5, 2006, following a run in San Francisco.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The revival closed on August 17, 2008, after 759 performances and 18 previews.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] It cost $8 million to finance and recouped its investment in 19 weeks.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The production was directed by Bob Avian, with the choreography reconstructed by Baayork Lee, who had played Connie Wong in the original Broadway production.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The opening night cast included Paul McGill, Michael Berresse, Charlotte d'Amboise, Mara Davi, James T.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Lane, Tony Yazbeck, Heather Parcells, Alisan Porter, Jason Tam, Jessica Lee Goldyn, Deidre Goodwin, and Chryssie Whitehead.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] On April 15, 2008, Mario Lopez joined the cast as the replacement for Zach.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The production was the subject of the documentary film *Every Little Step*.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The production received two Tony Award nominations in 2007 for Featured Role (Charlotte d'Amboise) and Revival (Musical).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The original contract for *A Chorus Line* provided for sharing the revenue from the show with the directors and dancers that had attended the original workshop sessions.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] However, the contract did not specify revenue when the musical was revived in 2006.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] In February 2008, an agreement was reached between the dancers and Michael Bennett's estate.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] A 2008 U.S. touring production opened on May 4, 2008, at the Denver Center for the Performing Arts and toured through June 2009.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] This production featured Michael Gruber as Zach, Nikki Snelson as Cassie, Emily Fletcher as Sheila, and Gabrielle Ruiz as Diana.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] In 2012, the musical toured Australia, gaining much critical acclaim.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The same production and cast then came to Singapore, playing at the Marina Bay Sands, Sands Theater from May 4 to 27, 2012.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The show returned to London for a West End revival in February 2013 at the London Palladium, running through August of that year.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] It was directed by original choreographer Bob Avian, with John Partridge, Scarlett Strallen, and Victoria Hamilton-Barritt starring.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Lane is reprising his Broadway role and Leigh Zimmerman won the Laurence Olivier Award for Best Performance in a Supporting Role in a Musical for her portrayal of Sheila in this production.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Producers announced on June 9, 2013, that the London revival cast would record a new cast album featuring never-before-heard songs which were written for the show but never made the final cut.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] In 2015, the Original Broadway cast of *Hamilton* paid tribute to *A Chorus Line*'s 40th anniversary and performed "What I Did For Love", with the original cast of *A Chorus Line* joining them onstage.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] In 2016, reports indicated that a Broadway revival was being planned for 2025, in honor of the show's 50th anniversary.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] For its annual fully staged musical event, the Hollywood Bowl produced a limited run of A Chorus Line from July 29–31, 2016, directed and choreographed by Baayork Lee.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The cast included Sabrina Bryan as Valerie Clark, Robert Fairchild as Mike Costa, Spencer Liff as Larry, Ross Lynch as Mark Anthony, Mara Davi as Maggie Winslow, J.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Elaine Marcos as Connie Wong, Jason Tam as Paul San Marco, Leigh Zimmerman as Sheila Bryant, Mario Lopez as Zach, Sarah Bowden as Cassie Ferguson, Krysta Rodriguez as Diana Morales, and Courtney Lopez as Kristine Ulrich.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] In 2016, approval was granted to director Donna Feore to allow changes in choreography so the show could be performed for the first time on a thrust stage, in the Festival Theatre at the Stratford Festival of Canada.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] In 2018, New York City Center presented *A Chorus Line* as their annual gala presentation.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The production was directed by Bob Avian, co-choreographer of the original 1975 production, and choreographed by Baayork Lee, Broadway's original Connie Wong.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] In 2019, a Spanish-language version of the musical premiered as part of the inaugural season of Teatro del Soho in Málaga, Spain, starring the theater's founder Antonio Banderas as Zach.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Banderas also co-directed the musical with Baayork Lee.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] On July 27, 2025, a one night *A Chorus Line Official 50th Anniversary Celebration* was held at the Shubert Theatre.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Original 1975 Broadway cast members Kelly Bishop, Wayne Cilento, Baayork Lee, Priscilla Lopez, and Donna McKechnie participated, and included special performances by Charlotte d’Amboise, Ariana DeBose, and Bebe Neuwirth, among others.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The performance was directed by Baayork Lee and included original choreography by Michael Bennett and Bob Avian.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The performance benefited the Entertainment Community Fund programs serving dancers.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] In 1975, the rights for a film were sold to Universal Pictures for $5.5 million plus 20% of the distributor's gross rentals above $30 million.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Universal subsequently sold the rights to PolyGram.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The film was released in 1985, starring Michael Douglas as Zach.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] It also featured Alyson Reed and Terrance Mann as Cassie and Larry respectively.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The film was directed by Richard Attenborough with a screenplay by Arnold Schulman.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] It was produced by Cy Feuer and distributed by Columbia Pictures, Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer, and Universal Pictures.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] The film received mixed reviews from critics and was a box office bomb, grossing only $14 million from a $25 million budget.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] Songs "Montage Part 1: Hello Twelve, Hello Thirteen, Hello Love" and "Montage Part 4: Gimme The Ball" were cut and replaced with "Surprise, Surprise", a new song written by Marvin Hamlisch and Edward Kleban.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] "The Music and the Mirror" was also cut and replaced with "Let Me Dance for You", written by Hamlisch and Kleban.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-chorus-line] "What I Did for Love" was sung by Cassie instead of Diana and was sung as a counterpart during "The Tap Combination." Songs "And...", and "Sing!" were cut entirely.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] The play consists of several interconnecting plots, connected by a celebration of the wedding of Duke Theseus of Athens and the Amazon queen Hippolyta.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Most of the action occurs in the woodland realm of Fairyland, under the light of the moon.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] The play opens with Theseus and Hippolyta who are four days away from their wedding.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Theseus is unhappy about how long he has to wait while Hippolyta thinks it will pass by like a dream.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Theseus is confronted by Egeus and his daughter Hermia, who is in love with Lysander, and resistant to her father's demand that she marry Demetrius, whom he has arranged for her to marry.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Enraged, Egeus invokes an ancient Athenian law before Duke Theseus, whereby a daughter needs to marry a suitor chosen by her father, or else face death.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Theseus offers her another choice: lifelong chastity as a nun worshipping the goddess Diana, but the two lovers both deny his choice and make a secret plan to escape into the forest for Lysander's aunt's house, to run away from Theseus.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Hermia tells their plans to Helena, her best friend, who pines unrequitedly for Demetrius, who broke up with her to be with Hermia.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Desperate to reclaim Demetrius's love, Helena tells Demetrius about the plan and he follows them in hopes of finding Hermia.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] The mechanicals, Peter Quince and fellow players Nick Bottom, Francis Flute, Robin Starveling, Tom Snout and Snug plan to put on a play for the wedding of the Duke and the Queen, "the most lamentable comedy and most cruel death of Pyramus and Thisbe".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Quince reads the names of characters and bestows them on the players.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Nick Bottom, who is playing the main role of Pyramus, is over-enthusiastic and wants to dominate others by suggesting himself for the characters of Thisbe, the Lion, and Pyramus at the same time.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Quince insists that Bottom can only play the role of Pyramus.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Bottom would also rather play a tyrant and recites some lines of Ercles.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Bottom is told by Quince that he would play the Lion so terribly as to frighten the duchess and other ladies so much that the Duke and Lords would have the players hanged.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Snug remarks that he needs Lion's part because he is "slow of study".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Quince assures Snug that the role of the lion is "nothing but roaring." Quince then ends the meeting by telling his actors "At the Duke's oak we meet".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] In a parallel plot line, at the same time, Oberon, king of the fairies, and Titania, his queen, have come to the forest outside Athens.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Titania tells Oberon that she plans to stay there until she has attended Theseus and Hippolyta's wedding.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Oberon and Titania are estranged because Titania refuses to give her Indian changeling to Oberon for use as his "knight" or "henchman" since the child's mother was one of Titania's worshippers.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] He calls upon Robin "Puck" Goodfellow, his "shrewd and knavish sprite", to help him concoct a magical juice derived from a flower called "love-in-idleness", which turns from white to purple when struck by Cupid's arrow.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] When the concoction is applied to the eyelids of a sleeping person, that person, upon waking, falls in love with the first living thing they perceive.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] He instructs Puck to retrieve the flower with the hope that he might make Titania fall in love with an animal of the forest and thereby shame her into giving up the little Indian boy.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] He says, "And ere I take this charm from off her sight, / As I can take it with another herb, / I'll make her render up her page to me." Helena and Demetrius enter, with her continuously making advances towards Demetrius, promising to love him more than Hermia.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] However, he rebuffs her with cruel insults.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Observing this, Oberon orders Puck to spread some of the magical juice from the flower on the eyelids of the young Athenian man.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] As Titania is lulled to sleep by her fairies, Oberon sneaks up and places the flower juice on her eyes, exiting the stage afterwards.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Lysander and Hermia enter, lost and exhausted from the journey.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Hermia rejects Lysander's advances to sleep together, and the two lie down on different corners.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Puck enters and mistakes Lysander for Demetrius, not having seen either before, and administers the juice to the sleeping Lysander.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Helena, coming across him, wakes him while attempting to determine whether he is dead or asleep.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Upon this happening, Lysander immediately falls in love with Helena.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Helena, mistakenly accusing Lysander of mocking her, runs away.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] When Hermia wakes up after dreaming a snake ate her heart, she sees that Lysander is gone and goes out in the woods to find him.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Meanwhile, Quince and his band of five labourers ("rude mechanicals", as Puck describes them) have arranged to perform their play about Pyramus and Thisbe for Theseus's wedding and venture into the forest, near Titania's bower, for their rehearsal.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Quince leads the actors in their rehearsal of the play.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Bottom is spotted by Puck, who (taking his name to be another word for a jackass) transforms his head into that of a donkey.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] When Bottom returns for his next lines, the other workmen run screaming in terror: They claim that they are haunted, much to Bottom's confusion.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Determined to await his friends, he begins to sing to himself.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Titania, having received the love potion, is awakened by Bottom's singing and immediately falls in love with him.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] (In the words of the play, "Titania waked, and straightway loved an ass.") She lavishes him with her attention and that of her fairies; while she is in this state of devotion, Oberon takes the changeling boy.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Oberon sees Demetrius still following Hermia.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] When Demetrius goes to sleep, Oberon condemns Puck's mistake and sends him to get Helena while he charms Demetrius's eyes.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Upon waking, Demetrius sees Helena arguing with Lysander, and instantly falls in love with her.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Now under the spell, the two men are both in love with a Helena convinced that both of her two suitors are mocking her, as neither loved her originally.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Hermia finds Lysander and asks why he left her, but Lysander claims he never loved Hermia, instead loving Helena.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] This soon turns into a quarrel between the two ladies, with Helena chiding Hermia for joining in the mockery session, followed by the latter furiously charging at her for stealing her true love's heart and blaming her for the supposed 'mockery'.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Oberon and Puck decide that they must resolve this conflict, and by the morning, none of them will have any memory of what happened, as if it were a dream.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Oberon arranges everything so Helena, Hermia, Demetrius, and Lysander will all believe they have been dreaming when they awaken.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Puck distracts Lysander and Demetrius from fighting over Helena's love by mimicking their voices and leading them apart.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Eventually, all four find themselves separately falling asleep in the glade.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Once they fall asleep, Puck administers the antidote to Lysander, returning his love to Hermia again.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Once they awaken, the lovers assume that whatever happened was a dream and not reality.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Having achieved his goals, Oberon releases Titania and orders Puck to remove the donkey's head from Bottom.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] The fairies then disappear, and Theseus and Hippolyta arrive on the scene, during an early morning hunt.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] They find the lovers still sleeping in the glade.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] They wake up the lovers and, since Demetrius no longer loves Hermia, Theseus over-rules Egeus's demands and arranges a group wedding.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] The lovers at first believe they are still in a dream and cannot recall what has happened.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] The lovers decide that the night's events must have been a dream, as they walk back to Athens.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] After they exit, Bottom awakes, and he too decides that he must have experienced a dream "past the wit of man" and declares that he will get Peter Quince to write a Ballad of the previous night's dream.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Fittingly called "Bottom's Dream", Bottom decides that he will sing the ballad after the end of their play, when Thisbe dies.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] At Quince's house, Quince and his team of actors worry that Bottom has gone missing.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Quince laments that Bottom is the only man who can take on the lead role of Pyramus.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Bottom returns and the actors get ready to put on "Pyramus and Thisbe".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] In the final scene of the play, Theseus, Hippolyta and the lovers watch the six workmen perform *Pyramus and Thisbe* in Athens.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] The mechanicals are so terrible at playing their roles that the guests laugh as if it were meant to be a comedy, and everyone retires to bed.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Afterwards, Oberon, Titania, Puck, and other fairies enter, and bless the house and its occupants with good fortune.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] After all the other characters leave, Puck "restores amends" and suggests that what the audience experienced might just be a dream.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] In 1775, Jerry Cruncher flags down the nightly mail-coach en route from London to Dover.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Cruncher is an employee of Tellson's Bank in London; he carries a message for Jarvis Lorry, one of the bank's managers.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Lorry sends Jerry back with the cryptic response "Recalled to Life", referring to Alexandre Manette, a French physician who has been released from the Bastille after an 18-year imprisonment.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Manette's daughter Lucie and her governess, Miss Pross.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Believing her father to be dead, Lucie faints at the news that he is alive.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Lorry takes her to France for a reunion.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] In the Paris neighbourhood of the Faubourg Saint-Antoine, Dr.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Manette has been given lodgings by his former servant Ernest Defarge and his wife Therese, the owners of a wine shop.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Lorry and Lucie find him in a small garret where he spends much of his time distractedly and obsessively making shoes – a skill he learned in prison.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Lorry and Lucie take him back to England.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] In 1780, French émigré Charles Darnay is on trial in London for treason against the British Crown.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] The key witnesses against him are two British spies, John Barsad and Roger Cly.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Barsad claims that he would recognise Darnay anywhere, but Darnay's lawyer points out that his colleague in court, Sydney Carton, bears a strong resemblance to the prisoner.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] With Barsad's testimony thus undermined, Darnay is acquitted.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] In Paris, the hated and abusive Marquis St.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Evrémonde orders his carriage to be driven recklessly fast through the crowded streets, hitting and killing a child.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] The Marquis contemptuously tosses a coin at the child's father, Gaspard, to compensate him for his loss; as the Marquis drives on, the coin is flung back into the carriage.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Arriving at his country château, the Marquis meets Darnay, his nephew and heir.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Out of disdain for his aristocratic family the nephew has replaced his surname (St.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Evrémonde) with Darnay, an anglicised version of his mother's maiden name (D'Aulnais).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] He despises the Marquis' views that "Repression is the only lasting philosophy.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] The dark deference of fear and slavery ... will keep the dogs obedient to the whip, as long as this roof [looking up to it] shuts out the sky." That night, Gaspard creeps into the château and stabs and kills the Marquis in his sleep.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] He avoids capture for nearly a year, but is eventually hanged in the nearby village.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] In London, Carton confesses his love to Lucie, but quickly recognises that she does not love him.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] He nevertheless promises to "embrace any sacrifice for you and for those dear to you".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Manette's permission to wed Lucie, and he agrees.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] On the morning of the marriage, Darnay reveals his real name and lineage to Dr.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Manette, facts that Manette had asked him to withhold until that day.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Manette to revert to his obsessive shoemaking.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] He returns to sanity before their return from honeymoon, and the whole incident is kept secret from Lucie.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] As the years pass, Lucie and Charles raise a family in England: a son (who dies in childhood) and a daughter, little Lucie.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Carton, though he seldom visits, is accepted as a close friend and becomes a special favourite of little Lucie.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] In Paris in July 1789, the Defarges help to lead the storming of the Bastille, a symbol of royal tyranny.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Manette's former cell and searches it thoroughly.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Throughout the countryside, local officials and other representatives of the aristocracy are slaughtered, and the St.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Evrémonde château is burned to the ground.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] In 1792, Lorry travels to France to save important documents stored at Tellson's Paris branch from the chaos of the French Revolution.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Darnay receives a letter from Gabelle, one of his uncle's former servants who has been imprisoned by the revolutionaries, pleading for Darnay (now the Marquis St.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Without telling his family or revealing his position as the new marquis, Darnay also sets out for Paris.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] On his way to Paris, Darnay is arrested as a returning emigrated aristocrat and jailed in La Force Prison.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Manette, Lucie and her daughter, Jerry, and Miss Pross all move to Paris and take up lodgings near those of Lorry.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Fifteen months later Darnay is finally tried, and Dr.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Manette – viewed as a popular hero after his long imprisonment in the Bastille – testifies on his behalf.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Darnay is acquitted and released, but is re-arrested later that day.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] While running errands with Jerry, Miss Pross is amazed to run into her long-lost brother Solomon.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Now posing as a Frenchman, he is an employee of the revolutionary authorities and one of Darnay's gaolers.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Carton also recognises him – as Barsad, one of the spies who tried to frame Darnay at his trial in 1780.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Solomon is desperate to keep his true identity hidden, and Carton blackmails him into helping with a play by threatening to denounce him as an English spy.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Darnay's retrial the following day is based on new denunciations by the Defarges and on a manuscript that Defarge had found in Dr.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Defarge reads the manuscript to the tribunal.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Manette had recorded that his imprisonment was at the hands of the Evrémonde brothers (Darnay's father and uncle) after he had tried to report their crimes.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Darnay's uncle had kidnapped and raped a peasant girl.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Her brother, first hiding his remaining younger sister, had gone to confront the uncle, who ran him through with his sword.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Manette, both the elder sister and the brother died.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Manette's manuscript concludes by denouncing the Evrémondes, "them and their descendants, to the last of their race." The jury takes that as irrefutable proof of Darnay's guilt, and he is condemned to die by the guillotine the next afternoon.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] In the Defarges' wine shop, Carton discovers that Madame Defarge is the surviving sister of the peasant family, and he overhears her planning to denounce Lucie and her daughter.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] He visits Lorry and warns him that Lucie and her family must be ready to flee the next day.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] He extracts a promise that they will be waiting for him at 2 pm, ready to leave the instant he returns.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Shortly before the executions are due to begin, Carton puts his plan into effect.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] With Barsad's reluctant assistance, he gains access to Darnay's prison cell.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Carton drugs his lookalike and swaps places with him.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Then he has Barsad carry Darnay out to the carriage, where Lorry and the family are awaiting Carton.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] Meanwhile, Madame Defarge goes to Lucie's lodgings, hoping to apprehend her and her daughter.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] There she finds Miss Pross, who is waiting for Jerry so they can follow the family out of Paris.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] The two women struggle and Madame Defarge's pistol discharges, killing her and permanently deafening Miss Pross.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/a-tale-of-two-cities] As Carton waits to board the tumbril that will take him to his execution, he is approached by another prisoner, a seamstress.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The council has been under no overall control since 2002.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Since 2022 it has been led by a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrat coalition.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] It meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices at the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a royal burgh by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Elections for the council were only introduced in 1833.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to that the council was not an elected body; when vacancies arose the existing council appointed successors.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was historically part of Aberdeenshire, but the functions affecting the burgh which operated at county level were relatively few, largely being limited to judicial functions and lieutenancy.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] When elected county councils were created in 1890 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1889, Aberdeen Corporation was deemed capable of running county-level local government functions, and so the burgh was excluded from the area administered by Aberdeenshire County Council.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] In 1891 Aberdeen's boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The historic county boundary between Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire in this area followed the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Following the absorption of Torry on the south bank of the river in 1891, the city straddled the two counties.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899, removing the city from the two counties for lieutenancy and other purposes as well as local government functions.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The city boundaries were subsequently enlarged several times, gaining further territory from both Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire, notably in 1935, 1952 and 1970.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Local government across Scotland was reorganised in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973, which replaced the counties, burghs and landward districts with a two-tier system of regions and districts.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] One of the districts was called 'City of Aberdeen', which formed part of Grampian Region.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] City of Aberdeen District Council was therefore a lower-tier district authority, with upper-tier regional functions being provided by Grampian Regional Council.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The City of Aberdeen district covered a larger area than the pre-1975 city, taking in the parishes of Dyce, Newhills, Old Machar, and Peterculter from Aberdeenshire and Nigg from Kincardineshire.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] All except Dyce had previously ceded territory to the city in pre-1975 boundary changes.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Nigg added in 1975 just covered the residual rural parts of the old parish around Cove Bay; Nigg village itself had been absorbed into the city in 1935.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Old Machar was named after St Machar's Cathedral in Old Aberdeen, which had been absorbed into the city in 1891; the parish of Old Machar that was absorbed in 1975 was just the residual part of the cathedral's old parish which lay north of the River Don, including Bridge of Don.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Local government was reorganised again in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] (Scotland) Act 1994, which abolished the regions and districts created in 1975 and established 32 single-tier council areas across Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The existing City of Aberdeen District became one of the new council areas.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The 1994 Act named the new council area 'City of Aberdeen', but this was changed to 'Aberdeen City' by a council resolution on 9 May 1995, before the new council area came into force, allowing the new council to take the name 'Aberdeen City Council'.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Following the 2022 election a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrats coalition took control of the council.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The first election to the City of Aberdeen District Council was held in 1974, initially operating as a shadow authority alongside the outgoing authorities until the new system came into force on 16 May 1975.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] A shadow authority was again elected in 1995 ahead of the change to council areas which came into force on 1 April 1996.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The role of Lord Provost of Aberdeen is largely ceremonial.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] They chair full council meetings and act as the council's civic figurehead.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Political leadership is provided by the leader of the council.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen City Council currently comprises 45 councillors, who represent the city's wards, and is headed by the Lord Provost.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2012 council election there were 43 members of Aberdeen City Council.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2003 and 2007, the council was under the control of a Liberal Democrat and Conservative coalition, holding 23 of the 43 seats on the council.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2003 election, the council had been considered a Labour stronghold.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Two Liberal Democrat councillors became independents during this period due to personal controversies, while the four strong Conservative group split in August 2010, with two councillors forming the Scottish Conservative Group and two others the Aberdeen Conservative Group.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] After the May 2012 election, the control of the council shifted back to the Labour Party, supported in a coalition by three Conservative and three Independent councillors, giving the administration 23 seats.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The Labour/Conservative/Independent coalition continued after the 2017 election, but with a change in the balance of power within the coalition.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Labour were reduced to nine councillors (subsequently suspended from membership by the Scottish Labour Party for forming a coalition with the Conservatives), whilst the Conservatives had eleven councillors elected.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] These Conservative and suspended "Aberdeen Labour" councillors were joined in coalition by three Independent councillors, one of who had left the Liberal Democrats just days after the council election.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] In December 2019 a councillor elected as a Conservative became an Independent following his conviction for sexual assault.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] This led to the ruling coalition becoming a minority administration comprising only 22 of the 45 councillors.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2017 and 2021 the council had Co-Leaders Douglas Lumsden (Conservative) and Jenny Laing (“Aberdeen Labour”) as a result of the coalition agreement.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Following Douglas Lumsden's election to the Scottish Parliament in May 2021 Jenny Laing became sole Leader of the council.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] After the 2022 election the SNP and Liberal Democrats agreed to form a partnership to lead the Council for the next five years.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] At the Council's statutory meeting on 18 May 2022, SNP councillor David Cameron was elected Lord Provost and Liberal Democrat Councillor Steve Delaney was elected Depute Provost.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] SNP Group Leader Alex Nicoll and Liberal Democrat Group Leader Ian Yuill became Co-Leaders of the Council.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Effective April 2, 2026, Desmond Buchanan, Councillor for George Street/Harbour ward resigned.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The Returning Officer announced the By-Election will take place on Thursday, June 25th 2026.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Council meetings are held at Aberdeen Town House on Broad Street, which was built in 1874 and substantially extended in 1975, including a new council chamber.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The council's main offices are now in the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The council moved into the renovated former college building in 2011.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Before May 2007, councillors represented 43 single-member wards election on a first-past-the-post basis.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] On 3 May 2007, the single transferable vote system was used for the first time and multi-member wards were introduced, each ward electing three or four councillors.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] The Local Government Boundary Commission for Scotland completed its final recommendations for new wards for all the council areas of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen is divided into 13 multi-member wards, electing a total of 45 councillors.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-city-council] This system was introduced as a result of the Local Governance (Scotland) Act 2004, and is designed to produce a form of proportional representation.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Formed in 1903 as a result of the amalgamation of three clubs from Aberdeen, they rarely challenged for honours until the post-war decade, when they won each of the major Scottish trophies under manager Dave Halliday.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This level of success was surpassed in the 1980s, when, under the management of Alex Ferguson, they won three league titles, four Scottish Cups and a Scottish League Cup, alongside the two European trophies.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen were the last club outside the Old Firm to win a league title, in 1984–85, and also the last Scottish team to win a European trophy.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] They have enjoyed less success since this golden era, though in the 2010s, the club ended a 19-year wait for a major trophy by winning the 2013–14 Scottish League Cup; this was followed by four consecutive seasons of finishing second behind Celtic in the league.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] More triumph came in 2025 as they won the Scottish Cup for the first time in 35 years.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen have played at Pittodrie Stadium since their inception.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The ground has a capacity of 19,274, and was the first all-seated and all-covered stadium in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Pittodrie was also the first football stadium to feature a dug-out, an invention of player and coach Donald Colman.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The club's colours have been primarily red and white since 1939; before this, they played in black and gold vertical stripes.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In modern times, Aberdeen have almost exclusively played with all-red strips with white detailing.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen attract support from the city and surrounding areas, as they have no geographically close rivals.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Lacking a local competitor, Aberdeen have instead developed rivalries with more distant opponents such as Dundee United (collectively known as the "New Firm" in the 1980s) and Rangers.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Before Aberdeen FC formed, in 1902 Edinburgh based Hibernian, unsettled in the capital, were looking to move to Aberdeen, even going as far as sending a valuer to Pittodrie to decide if the move was plausible.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This kickstarted talks of a merger between three clubs based in the city—Aberdeen, Victoria United and Orion—in 1903.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The three clubs came to an agreement and the new Aberdeen FC was formed.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The new club played its first match on 15 August 1903: a 1–1 draw with Stenhousemuir.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] That first season produced a win in the Aberdeenshire Cup, but only a third-place finish in the Northern League.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The club applied for membership of the Scottish League for the following season, and were elected to the Second Division.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In 1904, the club were managed by Jimmy Philip.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] At the end of its first season, despite having finished seventh out of twelve teams, Aberdeen were elected to the new, expanded First Division.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] They have remained in the top tier of Scottish football ever since.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] From 1906, the club made steady progress, with a Scottish Cup semi-final appearance in 1908 and another in 1911.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In that season of 1910–11, Aberdeen recorded their first victories over the Old Firm of Celtic and Rangers, and led the league for a time, but finished the season in second place.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Wartime affected the club as much as any other; despite spending cuts and other economies, by 1917 the situation became untenable.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen dropped out of competitive football, along with Dundee and Raith Rovers.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Senior football returned on 16 August 1919, and Aberdeen resumed with a fixture against Albion Rovers.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Philip was still in charge, and continued to oversee a team capable of isolated good results, but never quite able to sustain a challenge long enough to win a trophy.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In 1923, Aberdeen were drawn against Peterhead in the Scottish Cup, and posted their record score—a 13–0 victory.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Philip retired a year later, and was replaced as manager by Paddy Travers.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] He presided over the team's first Scottish Cup final in 1937.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Travers' "trainer"—first team coach in modern parlance—was former player Donald Colman.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Colman conceived the dug-out, a covered area set slightly below the level of the playing surface to better aid his observations.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Everton visited Pittodrie soon after its introduction, and exported the idea to the English leagues, from where it spread throughout the football-playing world.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Travers left to become manager of Clyde in 1939.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Travers was replaced by former Yeovil Town manager Dave Halliday, one of more than a hundred applicants for the role, and the club moved from their black and gold strip to red and white.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Halliday had barely begun his work when World War II halted competitive football in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] For these six years, the club was temporarily taken over by then-directors Charles B Forbes and George Anderson while Halliday served in the war.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Halliday's place in the Aberdeen Hall of Fame was secured after the war when he became the first manager to bring national trophies to Pittodrie.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen won the Southern League Cup in the 1945–46 season, defeating Rangers 3–2 at Hampden.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] They then reached the 1947 Scottish Cup final, defeating Hibernian 2–1 with George Hamilton, signed from Halliday's former club Queen of the South, scoring to gain the club's first major trophy.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] From this early success, Halliday's side reached two more Scottish Cup finals, in 1953 and 1954, though they lost both.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Halliday's team were not to be denied, however, and the following season, 1954–55, Aberdeen won their first Scottish League title.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Though league winners, the club did not participate in the first European Cup competition—Scotland's place was awarded to Hibernian, who took part by special invitation.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Halliday and Hamilton left at the end of that championship-winning season, and Halliday was replaced by Davie Shaw.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen won the League Cup under his guidance, beating St Mirren in 1955–56, and reached another Scottish Cup final in 1959.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] However, Shaw stepped aside for another former favourite player, Tommy Pearson, in 1959.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Pearson's time in charge coincided with a high turnover of players, and yielded no trophies.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] He retired in 1965, making way for Eddie Turnbull.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Turnbull led Aberdeen to the 1967 Scottish Cup final, where the side was ultimately defeated by Celtic.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Despite this loss, Aberdeen qualified for the European Cup Winner's Cup in the following season thanks to their appearance in this final, the first time the club had competed in European competition.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Their first tie was a 14–1 aggregate victory over KR Reykjavik, although they lost the second round tie with Standard Liège 3–2 on aggregate.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Two years later, Derek "Cup-tie" McKay recorded the only four goals of his Aberdeen career to help his team to the 1969–70 Scottish Cup, scoring the winning goals in the quarter- and semi-final, and two in the final itself.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] As Scottish Cup holders, Aberdeen once again qualified for the same competition, but were eliminated in the first round following a 4–4 aggregate tie with Honvéd.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This tie, level after extra time and also level on away goals, was decided by the first penalty shoot-out in UEFA competition history, Honvéd winning the shootout 5–4 in Budapest.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The Aberdeen side of the 1970s regularly challenged for domestic honours.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] However, they rarely won trophies, with the exception of the Drybrough Cup in 1971 under Jimmy Bonthrone and the League Cup in 1976, under Ally MacLeod.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] During this decade, Aberdeen had five managers: Eddie Turnbull, Jimmy Bonthrone, Ally MacLeod, Billy McNeill and Alex Ferguson.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] They reached two more national cup finals—the Scottish Cup in 1978 under Billy McNeill and the League Cup in the following season under the new manager Alex Ferguson.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Under Ferguson's guidance, the club won three league championships, four Scottish Cups, one League Cup, the European Cup Winner's Cup, the European Super Cup and a Drybrough Cup—all in the space of seven years.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Players such as Jim Leighton, Willie Miller, Alex McLeish and Gordon Strachan became the backbone of the team.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen's second League title was won in 1979–80 and this initial success was built upon with Scottish Cup wins in three successive seasons from 1982 to 1984, and two more league titles in 1983–84 and 1984–85.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] During the European Cup Winners' Cup in 1983, Aberdeen beat FC Sion, Dinamo Tirana and Lech Poznań to face the German Cup winners Bayern Munich.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This game was won 3–2 at Pittodrie after a goalless draw in Germany, John Hewitt with the winning goal.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] They then faced now-defunct Belgian club Waterschei in the semi-final.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen beat them 5–1 at home, and lost for the first time in the tournament, 1–0 away, resulting in an aggregate victory which sent Aberdeen to the final.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] On 11 May 1983, Aberdeen beat Real Madrid 2–1 after extra time to win the cup and become only the third Scottish side to win a European trophy.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The club released a song, "European Song", to coincide with the appearance in the final.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This was followed up with the capture of the European Super Cup in December, when Hamburger SV were beaten over two legs.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen reached the semi-finals of the 1983–84 European Cup Winners' Cup, before losing to Porto 2–0 on aggregate.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In the first round of the 1984–85 European Cup Aberdeen lost to East Berlin side BFC Dynamo in a penalty shoot-out, following a 3–3 draw on aggregate.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Today, both clubs enjoy friendly relations.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] After Ferguson moved to England to manage Manchester United in November 1986, Aberdeen struggled to compete with Celtic and a resurgent Rangers.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen signed new co-managers in 1989, pairing Alex Smith and Jocky Scott.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] A number of foreign players were signed, including Dutch internationals Theo Snelders and Hans Gillhaus.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In the 1989–90 season, the club won both the Scottish Cup and the Scottish League Cup.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In 1991, they lost the last game of the season, and the league title, to Rangers.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Former player Willie Miller took over in 1992 and presided over two seasons where Aberdeen came close to winning the title.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] However, the club ended the 1994–95 season second-bottom, and had to rely on a play-off victory over Dunfermline Athletic to retain their Premier Division status.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Miller was sacked in February 1995, and replaced by Roy Aitken.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Despite a Scottish League Cup success in 1995, the club continued to struggle.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen's first foreign manager, Ebbe Skovdahl, was appointed in 1999 and his time in charge coincided with some of the heaviest defeats in the club's history.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The low point of the club's history came in the 1999–2000 season, where they finished bottom of the table.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] As the Scottish Premier League (SPL) was being expanded to twelve teams, Aberdeen were due to take part in a three team play-off with the teams that finished second and third in the First Division.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The play-off never happened though, as one of those clubs (Falkirk) did not meet SPL stadium requirements, and Aberdeen retained their top flight status.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This was followed by an early-season defeat to Irish club Bohemians on the away goals rule in the next season's UEFA Cup.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Steve Paterson was appointed to replace Skovdahl following his resignation in 2002, but lasted only two seasons.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Paterson's tenure with Aberdeen was marred by his addiction to alcohol.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In March 2003 he failed to attend a home game against Dundee due to being too hungover after a night of drinking prior to the match.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Jimmy Calderwood took over in 2004 and Aberdeen posted more consistent results than in previous seasons.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In the 2006–07 season, the club finished in third place in the league and entered the final qualifying round for the 2007–08 UEFA Cup.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen defeated Dnipro on the away goals rule to progress (the first time Aberdeen had won on away goals in European football for 40 years).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] They went on to beat Copenhagen 4–0, in a game which saw one of Pittodrie's biggest crowds since the 1980s.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This set up a meeting with German giants Bayern Munich, which they lost 7–3 on aggregate after a 2–2 draw which saw Aberdeen lead twice in the first leg.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Calderwood was sacked by Aberdeen on 24 May 2009, hours after he took the club to a fourth-place finish and back into Europe.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Poor domestic cup performances were thought to be the reason for Calderwood's dismissal.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Mark McGhee of Motherwell was appointed as Calderwood's replacement in June 2009.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] McGhee controversially dismissed Aberdeen legend and goalkeeping coach Jim Leighton in August 2009 and replaced him with Colin Meldrum.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen suffered a 9–0 defeat to Celtic on 6 November 2010, their heaviest ever defeat.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] McGhee and his assistants were eventually sacked in December of that year.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen approached Craig Brown, who was working without a contract at Motherwell, to replace McGhee.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Brown initially rebuffed an offer, but after further discussions with the club Brown resigned as manager at Motherwell to be announced as the next manager at Aberdeen two days later.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The first act of the new management team of Brown and Archie Knox was to re-instate Leighton.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen failed to produce better results under Craig Brown's tenure, and in March 2013 he announced his retirement to take up a non-executive director role on the club's board.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Derek McInnes was announced as the successor to Craig Brown in March 2013.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In McInnes' first season as manager, Aberdeen won the 2013–14 Scottish League Cup after defeating Inverness 4–2 on penalties, their first trophy in 19 years.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen finished third in the Scottish Premiership, and began the next season by coming through the early rounds of the Europa League, beating Dutch club FC Groningen before eventually being eliminated by Spanish side Real Sociedad.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The club ended the season in second place—their best league position since 1993–94—in 2015, 2016, and 2017.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In recent seasons' Europa League competitions, they were defeated in the third qualifying round four times: In 2015–16 by FC Kairat, in 2016–17 by NK Maribor, in 2017–18 by Apollon Limassol, and in 2019–20 by HNK Rijeka.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen were league runners-up once more in 2016–17 and reached both cup finals, but were beaten 3–0 by Celtic in the League Cup and 2–1 by the same opponents in the Scottish Cup, echoing the outcome in 1992–93 when Aberdeen had finished second to Rangers in all competitions.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] They were again second the following season, earning a first league win against Celtic away from home for fourteen years in the final game of the season.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This qualified them for the 2018–19 UEFA Europa League, where they were defeated after extra time by Premier League side Burnley in the second qualifying round.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In November 2019, Major League Soccer side Atlanta United acquired a less than 10 percent stake in Aberdeen for £2 million (US$2.57 million) as part of a strategic alliance between the two clubs.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] As part of this deal, vice-chairman Dave Cormack became chairman of the club, replacing Stewart Milne.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Atlanta United president Darren Eales also took a seat on Aberdeen's board of directors.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] McInnes left the post of manager in March 2021 after almost eight years in charge.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Over the subsequent three years, Aberdeen went through four managers.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Neil Warnock briefly served as interim manager.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In April 2024, the club announced that Jimmy Thelin would take the role beginning in June 2024.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] On 24 May 2025, Aberdeen won their first Scottish Cup in 35 years after beating Celtic on penalties.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] For the first season of the club's existence, the team played in a predominantly white strip.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This is variously reported as all-white, or as white shirts with blue shorts and socks.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This colour scheme was the direct descendant of the colours worn by the precursor Aberdeen club, but lasted only one season before being replaced.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] For the 1904–05 season, Aberdeen adopted a black and gold striped shirt, which led to the team being nicknamed "the Wasps".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This strip, with only minor variations, was worn until just before the start of the Second World War.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The blue shorts lasted until 1911, and then were replaced with white ones.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Socks were black with gold trim, either as stripes or as a solid bar at the turndown.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] A representative post-war Aberdeen strip.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] These colours were worn for all the trophy-winning seasons of the 1950s.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In March 1939, Aberdeen changed the black and gold colours to red and white, reflecting the silver and red colours of the official City of Aberdeen arms.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The first red strips were worn with white shorts, with either red or white socks from 1939 until the 1965–66 season.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In 1966, Aberdeen adopted red shorts, making the official kit all-red, similar to that of Liverpool, who made a similar change at around the same time.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This arrangement has continued to the present day, with several variations in design, in common with most senior clubs as the replica shirt market has expanded.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In the late 1970s an Admiral strip featured five vertical white stripes on the left side of the shirt and shorts, and the early 1980s shirts—as worn at the 1983 European Cup Winners Cup final—featured white vertical pinstripes.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Later design changes included significant amounts of blue, and a one-season reversion to white shorts, although the all-red scheme returned in 1997.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Shirt sponsorship began in 1987, and the initial shirt sponsor was JVC.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Since then, with the club making fewer appearances on the international stage, shirt sponsors have tended to be local to Aberdeen—they have included one of the local commercial radio stations, Northsound, as well as several Aberdeen-based oil service companies.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] As of 2026, the current shirt sponsor is TEXO.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Away colours have tended to be either white—often with black shorts—or a combination of yellow and black, referring back to the black and gold strips of the pre-war era, although for a time in the 1970s, Aberdeen sported an all-blue change strip with white socks.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] For the 2007–08 season, the change strip was all-white, with a third kit of yellow and black halves available if needed for European games, or in the event of a clash involving both red and white.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The club did not have an official crest before 1972, but several variations on the letters AFC had from time to time featured on the shirt, usually in some kind of cursive font.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In November 1972, the club unveiled an official crest or logo, designed by Aberdonian graphic designer Donald Addison.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The design represented a capital letter *A* as the side view of a football goal, with a ball forming the crossbar of the letter.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This ball was crosshatched in such a way as to depict it as being inside the net, signifying the scoring of a goal.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The logo was completed by the letters *FC* in smaller type at a level with the ball element.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This badge was used on the shirts from around 1978, with no significant alterations until the mid-1980s when the words "Aberdeen Football Club" were added in a circular border, and the date of the club's founding, 1903, was added under the goal element.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The current version of the crest, which retains these elements in a unified design, was introduced at the start of the 1997–98 season.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Two stars signifying the winning of the two European trophies in 1983 were introduced over the badge in the 2005–06 season.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen have played throughout their existence at Pittodrie Stadium, the name of which comes from a Celtic term for "place of manure".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The ground was first used by the original Aberdeen F.C. in 1899, in a 7–1 win over Dumbarton; when they merged with two other teams in 1903, the new club took over the old Aberdeen ground.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] On 15 August 1903, 8,000 spectators turned up to watch the new Aberdeen draw 1–1 against Stenhousemuir, the first game played at Pittodrie by its amalgamated tenants.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The club initially rented the ground, but subsequently bought it in 1920.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The record attendance is 45,061, during a Scottish Cup match between Aberdeen and Hearts on 13 March 1954.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] A quarter of the South Stand is used to accommodate travelling supporters.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In 1978, Pittodrie became the first all covered, all-seater stadium in Britain.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen train at Cormack Park, which was opened on 31 October 2019 by former manager Alex Ferguson, who described the development as "up there with the best" that he had seen.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] As well as being a training centre for the first team, the complex is also home to the Bobby Clark Football Academy and the AFC Community Trust, as well as acting as a community sports hub.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The training facilities are named after chairman Dave Cormack, due to the significant financial investment he made to realise the completion of the project.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The complex is made up of a training pavilion, groundsman's accommodation, three full-sized training pitches, two floodlit 3G pitches and two grass pitches.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] There is also flexible outdoor and indoor space that can be used for sporting or recreational purposes.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] All the pitches are named after club legends, chosen by the fans via an online poll.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Prior to the opening of Cormack Park, the first team trained in a variety of locations around the city, including the local Gordon Barracks, Seaton Park, Aberdeen Sports Village and Countesswells, the playing fields of Robert Gordon's College.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Since 2009, Aberdeen have been examining a move to a new stadium.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Plans for a new stadium began when the club indicated that further development of Pittodrie Stadium was not possible due to the age of the ground and the restrictions from surrounding land.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen City Council approved an initial project in May 2009, to be situated near Loirston Loch in the south of the city, subject to planning permission.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In August 2010, a planning application for the new stadium was submitted to the council, which was approved the following February.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The move was delayed by a year in May 2012 due to problems with land ownership, and suffered a serious setback the following August, when the council rejected a joint application by Aberdeen and Cove Rangers to build a community sports centre at nearby Calder Park.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen announced in November 2014 new plans to instead build training facilities at Balgownie, on land owned by the University of Aberdeen, but the project was ultimately scrapped in the following July.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Plans to develop a new stadium and training facilities near Westhill, close to the newly developed Aberdeen Western Peripheral Route, were announced in May 2016.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The new stadium is expected to have a similar capacity to Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Although the project overcame legal challenges from local residents, progress stalled due to the economic impact of the COVID-19 pandemic in Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Alternative designs at the city's beachfront close to Pittodrie were released in August 2021.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen's supporters, known as the Red Army, are listed in the team squad list as wearing the number 12 shirt.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen are the only top-flight team in the third largest city in Scotland, a city which is relatively remote, geographically, from other large population centres, and as a result have a large catchment area of potential supporters.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The average attendance in the 2023–24 Scottish Premiership was 16,055.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In the 1980s, a minority of the club's supporters had a reputation as one of Britain's most prominent casuals groups, the Aberdeen Soccer Casuals.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The rise of the Aberdeen Casuals coincided with the most successful period in the club's history, and has been chronicled in more than one published account.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Whilst numbers have steadily declined with the introduction of Football Banning Orders preventing hooligans from travelling to games, the Aberdeen Casuals still appear at big fixtures often away from home and in the UEFA Europa League.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] There were clashes at both fixtures against FC Groningen in 2014, as well as 13 arrests after violent clashes with Dundee United fans at a game in December 2015.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen have rarely played in the same division as their geographically closest neighbours (Cove Rangers, Peterhead, Brechin City, Montrose, Arbroath, Elgin City, and Forfar Athletic), so rivalries have tended to come from further afield.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Cove Rangers from the same city entered the professional leagues for the first time in 2019, although the Aberdeen derby is yet to occur in a league meeting.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In the early 1980s, owing to the success both domestically and in Europe of Aberdeen and Dundee United, the pair were known as the New Firm.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] However, Dundee United have their city neighbours Dundee as close rivals, and the antagonism was not always reciprocated to the same degree.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The same situation applies to Aberdeen's rivalry with Rangers, in that Rangers have their own much older and well-known Old Firm rivalry with Celtic.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Manager Alex Ferguson's personal history with Rangers also played a role: a boyhood fan and once the club's record signing, Ferguson had long believed that Rangers had frozen him out of the club after they discovered his wife was a Roman Catholic.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In the 2021 documentary *Sir Alex Ferguson: Never Give In*, he admitted that his remarks after Aberdeen won the 1983 Scottish Cup final (where, despite Aberdeen beating Rangers 1–0, he regarded it as a "disgraceful performance") were born from a desire to win by a larger margin.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] There are still often violent clashes between both sets of supporters within and outwith the stadium to this day.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen developed a minor rivalry with Inverness Caledonian Thistle since Inverness were first promoted to the SPL in 2004.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] It is known as the North derby, since Aberdeen and Inverness are the two largest settlements in the north of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen's re-emerged as one of the top teams in Scotland during the 2010s, which increased the rivalry with Celtic both competitively and between supporters.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] There have been minor incidents at games.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen are known as "The Dons", a name that has been in use since at least 1913.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] One theory is that it derives from the word "don" meaning "teacher", given Aberdeen's history as a university town.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] It may also be a reference to the nearby River Don, or a contraction of "Aberdonians".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Before the popular adoption of "The Dons", the team were variously known as "The Wasps" or "The Black and Golds", both names a reference to the yellow and black striped shirts of the time.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] As with many teams that play in red, Aberdeen may also be called "The Reds", and are referred to by some supporters as "The Dandy Dons" or "The Dandies".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Rival clubs occasionally refer to Aberdeen as "The Sheep" and their supporters as "The Sheep Shaggers".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The term was eventually accepted by the club's supporters, and fans began chanting "the sheep are on fire" at games.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The song was originally sung by away fans poking fun at an Aberdeen fan set on fire on a train while wearing a homemade sheep costume.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] This in turn led to specialised merchandise being sold by the club and local businesses.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Chants and songs include "The Northern Lights of Old Aberdeen" and "Stand Free", the latter of which is set to the tune of "Lord of the Dance".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen has had a few ultras groups over its lifetime.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In 1999, a group of supporters formed a fan group called the red ultras; this group came together in making displays over its lifetime such as their "one love" display and their "red ultras" display.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The red ultras disbanded at the beginning of 2010.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Following the introduction of the "Red Shed", a new group going by the name of "Ultras Aberdeen" formed in 2022 and have made displays such as the "Heroes" display in tribute to 1983 European Cup Winners' Cup final.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] There was also a display at Hampden Park for the 2023 Viaplay League Cup final against Rangers.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] The group has also been responsible for surfing flag displays as well the use of pyrotechnics such as smoke bombs and flares.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Note: Flags indicate national team as defined under FIFA eligibility rules; some limited exceptions apply.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Players may hold more than one non-FIFA nationality.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Aberdeen inaugurated a Hall of Fame as part of the club's centenary celebrations in 2003.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Six players were inducted following the initial dinner in March 2004, and a further six were included in November 2004.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Ex-manager Alex Ferguson was inducted at a re-launch event in November 2015.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In 2017, Neale Cooper, Archie Knox, John McMaster and Graham Leggat were inducted into the Hall of Fame.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In 2018, Eoin Jess, Peter Weir, Bobby Clark and Donald Colman were inducted.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Matt Armstrong, Brian Irvine, Hans Gillhaus, and Charlie Nicholas were inducted in January 2025.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] In November 2015, supporters cast votes to determine the greatest ever Aberdeen team.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] All players are from Scotland unless otherwise stated.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] Competitive, professional matches only, up to the end of the 2025–26 season.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] 2. source has 159 goals/292 games, but 4 goals/8 games were from unofficial wartime league fixtures in 1945/46.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-football-club] 3. source has Willie Cooper 394 games/3 goals, but 17 games/0 goals were from unofficial wartime league fixtures in 1945/46.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-scotland-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The Student Show has been held every year since 1921 (with the exception of 2020 due to the COVID-19 pandemic).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] From the start it has involved a number of young writers, performers and musicians.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The show is staged in Aberdeen largest professional theatre, His Majesty’s Theatre.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The Student Show is coordinated by its Administrator’s Team and performed by students of The University of Aberdeen, Robert Gordon University and North East Scotland College.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] It is generally written and produced by former students and show alumni.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] In 1920, at the prompting of the authorities at Aberdeen Royal Infirmary, the students' representative council (SRC) of Aberdeen University established a series of fund-raising events in aid of local hospitals; central to which was the annual Gala Week.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] In 1921 the Gala Week opened with the first Student Show, a mock trial (of a breach of promise case) held in the Aberdeen University Debating Chamber ("The Debater") at Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The Gala Week Committee then invited the University Debating Society to stage an annual musical comedy or revue based on student life.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The first of these, in 1922, ‘Stella, the Bajanella’ was written by then undergraduate Eric Linklater with music by JS Taylor.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The Show then became an annual event, performed in various venues in Aberdeen, including the Training Centre Hall in St.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Andrew Street, the Aberdeen College Hall and the Palace Theatre in 1927 and 1928, before finding a home in His Majesty's Theatre in 1929.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Since then it has occasionally been performed elsewhere in the city, when His Majesty's Theatre was unavailable – the Aberdeen College of Education in 1981 and 1982, the Music Hall in 2004 and His Majesty's Theatre – Hilton (the former College of Education theatre) in 2005.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The Student Show was produced every year in Aberdeen without a break from 1921, including throughout World War II, until 2020, when for the first time the show was cancelled, due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The cast is made up of volunteer students.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] They intensively rehearse each new show during the Easter academic vacation.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The following week - the first of the academic summer term - they perform the show, generally in the evenings, in front of paying audiences.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The 2019 Student Show, 'The Glaikit Showman' was staged at His Majesty's Theatre, raised £122,000 for 36 different local charities.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Previous years had brought more modest returns.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Among those who were associated with the Student Show in its earlier years were Eric Linklater, Sonia Dresdel, Stephen Mitchell, Moultrie Kelsall, and Andrew Cruickshank.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Participants from later in the 20th Century include playwright and educationalist James Scotland and members of The Flying Pigs.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Novelist, historian and playwright, Eric Linklater (director 1922–24) wrote and directed the first Student Show proper; 'Stella, the Bajanella'.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] His play 'To Meet the Macgregors' was performed as the Student Show in 1946.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] This was during his tenure as Rector of Aberdeen University from 1945 to 1948.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Raitt (known as "Rab The Rhymer") (director 1931, 1933–34, 1938–39) was a marine biologist who worked in the Marine Laboratory in the Aberdeen district of Torry.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He was also a popular radio performer, singing at the piano in broadcasts from the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) Aberdeen Studios.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He died age 41 as a result of an accident with a car on 4 October 1944.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The shows from 1935 to 1939 were musical comedies, mostly written by students under Raitt's direction.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The 1933 show 'Town and Gown' was rewritten extensively and presented in its new form for a week in September 1934.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] This unusual timing for Student Show, during the university long vacation, was so as to coincide on 10 and 11 September 1934 with the third visit to Aberdeen of the British Association for the Advancement of Science.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Moultrie Kelsall, while head of the British Broadcasting Corporation's Aberdeen Radio Station, 2BD, produced 'Aurora Borealis' in 1932.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Kelsall subsequently had a 30-year acting career in television and movies.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Reginald Barrett-Ayres (1920–1981), a graduate of Edinburgh University, was Director of Music at the Quaker Ackworth School near Pontefract, Yorkshire from 1942 to 45; and at Glasgow Academy from 1945 to 51.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He joined Aberdeen University's Department of Music and Drama, as a Lecturer in January 1951.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He became acting Head of Department in 1956 and remained in post (latterly, as Reader and Head of Department) until his death in a road accident at age 61.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He was an expert on the music of Haydn, particularly the string quartets.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] His own compositions included three operas, concertos for violin and double bass, operettas, choral works, solos, duets, anthems and hymns.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He was involved in many of the University's theatrical and musical productions, directing or co-directing an unsurpassed nine Student Shows between 1955 and 1965.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] With George Low he co-wrote the Show theme song "Spirit of Show".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] 'Laughing at Life', a show consisting of original music and arrangements, is listed as "c.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] 1961", but is likely to be the 1954 Student Show of the same title.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Hay Prestowe" (co-director 1944) was the pseudonym of Andrew Shivas.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] While he was an undergraduate at Aberdeen he played in the university dance orchestra, was a tympanist for the university symphony orchestra, a pipe band big drummer, and student show xylophonist.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He was also an accomplished conjurer, from which arose his pseudonym (a play on hey presto!), and co-founder, in 1925, of the Aberdeen Magical Society.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] A pathologist in later life in Edinburgh, Shivas died of a stroke in 1996.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Roddy Begg, director of the 1974, 1979 and 1983 Student Shows, and of the 2000 and 2005 reunions, has a lifelong interest in the theatre, acting and directing for Aberdeen's Studio Theatre Group (which he co-founded in the 1960s) and other dramatic and musical groups.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He was Director of the Edinburgh Festival Fringe Society and Honorary Vice President of Aberdeen Opera Company.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] A graduate of the University of Aberdeen, he was a member of staff for over three decades, as Secretary to the Faculties of Medicine and Science, Registry Officer, Clerk to the Senate, and Secretary to the University.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He retired as Secretary in 1999, taking up the post of Director of Alumni Relations.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He retired from the University in February 2002.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] In November 2006 he was awarded the Degree of Doctor of Honoris Causa by Aberdeen University, in recognition of his lifelong commitment to the Institution.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Charles Barron (1936-2012) was Student Show director 1977–78 and reunion co-director 2005.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He had a long and prolific tenure in the dramatic arts, Doric dialect and history of the Scottish North-East.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He graduated from Aberdeen University with a First Class Honours Degree in English Language and Literature, taught in Aberdeen and Inverurie, where began a 40-year association with Haddo House, as Shakespearean actor, Director of Operas, Arts Director and creator of the Youth Theatre.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] In 1970, he became Head of Speech and Drama at Aberdeen College of Education (later the Northern College of Education, which eventually became subsumed within Aberdeen University).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He was the award-winning author of the Doric plays ‘Fooshion’ and ‘Amang the Craws’.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Rhona Mitchell choreographed the 1978, 1979 and 1981 shows, and also directed in 1981.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] She has worked professionally on radio and stage and as a freelance voice coach, drama tutor and director for more than 25 years with Scottish Television, BBC Scotland and many theatres across Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] She founded the Mitchell School of Drama in Inverurie in 1983.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] She co-directed the Abderite Theatre Company, in which capacity she directed 'Gobi's Eyes' in 2004, and 'Ouch' in 2005.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] She also produced the first Garioch Theatre Festival in April 2005.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Ronnie Middleton, an Arts Graduate of Aberdeen University, mathematics teacher at Powis Academy and later Cults Academy, dancer, singer and multi-faceted actor, directed Student Show in 1986 and from 1988 to 90, co-directed the 2000 reunion and took part as cast member in many shows in the 1970s.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Ronnie was a prolific performer and director with local theatre groups.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He co-founded the Aberdeen Phoenix Theatre Company.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He was also closely involved in the Attic Theatre Company, in Powis Academy stage productions, Temporary Fault and Punchline, until his death from cancer in 2002.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Ronnie is also remembered for his secret, but well-known, fortnightly role at Pittodrie Stadium as Angus the Bull, Aberdeen Football Club's mascot.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] George Sinclair, formerly headmaster at Powis Academy, stage-managed 38 Student Shows from the 1950s, many of them with the assistance of Colin MacKenzie, who eventually succeeded him as stage manager of Show.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] During the same period George Sinclair also stage-managed 32 shows for the Aberdeen Lyric Musical Society.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The script editor for the 1951 Student Show 'Spring In Your Step' was Colin MacLean, who went on to be the founding editor, in 1965, of the *Times Educational Supplement*, Scotland, and from March 1979 to June 1990 was managing director (publishing) of Aberdeen University Press.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The 1922 theme song "Stella, the Bajanella", by R.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Taylor, became a popular anthem for many years.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] It was replaced in the 1950s by "Spirit of Show", written by George Low with music by Reginald Barrett-Ayres.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] "Spirit of Show" has since remained the traditional anthem of Student Show.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] 'Stella, the Bajanella' (1922) was apparently named for Stella Henriques, a medical student at Aberdeen University.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Bajan, a medieval term (literally 'yellow beak' – bec jaune), describing trainees in the pre-student year, was traditionally applied to Aberdeen University freshmen.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Female students were referred to as "bajanellas".
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] 1928's 'Admirable Crichton' was a production of The Admirable Crichton, a comedy play written in 1902 by Scotsman J.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Barrie, Rector of the University of St Andrews from 1919 to 1922.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Barrie's older brother, Alexander, graduated with honours in Classics at Aberdeen University in 1866.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Three shows use the local pronunciation of Footdee – 'Fittie': 'A Tale of Two Fitties' (2000), 'Fittie Woman' (2005) and ‘Fittie Fittie Bang Bang’ (2018).
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Many titles, traditionally, are puns and plays on other well-known theatrical titles, e.g.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] 'Folies Berserques' (1960) – Folies Bergère; 'Risques Galore' (1980) – Whisky Galore; 'A Coarse Line' (1986) – A Chorus Line; 'The Provost Of Oz' (1987) – *The Wizard of Oz*; 'Mounthooly The Magic Roundabout' (1990) – The Magic Roundabout; 'N.E.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Approximately 250 former cast members attended each reunion, of whom about 70 re-enacted sketches and musical numbers from former shows.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The oldest performer in the 2000 reunion was Duncan Murray, a retired doctor from Kent, who had appeared in the Show between 1942 and 1945.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] He sang "Rosemount Rosie", one of the most popular Student Show numbers of the 1940s.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] The theatrical society were hosted by Lord Provost David Cameron and Aberdeen City Council with a Civic Reception in the cities Beach Ballroom.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] This took place in May 2022 and celebrated 100 years of the charitable student association.
[src:aberdeen-student-show/aberdeen-student-show] Notable show alumni including Amy lamb, Alex Brown and John Hardie of The Flying Pigs spoke at the event.
